{"author":{"id":"5248ea2e55f6d1868efa8a8629139666b21cf7bd76aafdf39d9506b66d9427fd"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1495554610,"nonce":"KGAjchJRcP6XaDMq6zc17O6L/R4=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyMzA3NTgyMjM=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1323","origin":"github"},"title":"Best practices for FASTQ output formats","message":"While this is a general problem, it is based on a problem with my stacks clone_filter tool so I am pinging @bgruening and @abretaud .\n\nMy question is: what is the best practice for FASTQ output formats? Namely compressed versus uncompressed.\n\nI naively made the tool to always output compressed data. In my mind it makes sense: much less disk space occupied. But I had an immediate complain from a user that told me that some tools could not receive the output from clone_filter. I see several alternatives:\n\n1. My preferred is the one I implemented, as it saves disk space on potentially enormous files\n2. Another alternative is to use the same format for input as for output (so a compressed file gets compressed output and an uncompressed file gets uncompressed output). But this might be problematic if a tool further down the pipeline does not take whatever is the original format of the data\n3. Yet another is to allow the user to choose. But is it really needed to burden the user with this?\n4. Finally a hybrid between 2 and 3: Use the default from the input file, but allow the user to override.\n\nGenerally I think everything compressed would be the most sensical thing to do. But that is not possible.\n\n\nI will implement whatever you folks tell me its the best practice.\n\nThanks","files":null}]}